<div id="content_wrapper" class="longformpage">
	<!-- <h2></h2> -->
			<div class="longform post_img fullwidth">
			<img src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/Screenshot-2024-12-19-at-10.55.33 PM.png" alt="" class="entry_post"/>
		</div>
				<h1>The 10 Best Literary Adaptations of 2024</h1>
		<h2>Emotional Robots, Dangerous Conmen, Curious Clergymen, and More</h2>
    <div class="inner">
		<div class="post_header_wrapper">
    				</div>
				<div class="author_info" itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
			<div class="author_name">By&nbsp;<a href="https://lithub.com/author/oliviarutigliano/" itemprop="url"><span itemprop="name">Olivia&nbsp;Rutigliano</span></a></div>
			<div class="author_hr"><hr/></div>
			<div class="publish_date">December 20, 2024</div>
		</div>
		<div class="social_links">
						<a href="https://twitter.com/intent/tweet?via=lithub&text=The+10+Best+Literary+Adaptations+of+2024&url=https%3A%2F%2Flithub.com%2Fthe-10-best-literary-adaptations-of-2024%2F"><span class="social_twitter"></span></a>
			<a href="https://www.facebook.com/sharer.php?u=https%3A%2F%2Flithub.com%2Fthe-10-best-literary-adaptations-of-2024%2F&t=The+10+Best+Literary+Adaptations+of+2024"><span class="social_facebook"></span></a>
					</div>
    <div class="inner">
    	<!-- Begin main content -->
    	<div class="inner_wrapper fullwidth">
    			
										<!-- Begin each blog post -->
						<div class="post_wrapper" style="padding-top:0;">
							<div class="post_inner_wrapper">
						    	<div class="post_wrapper_inner">
										<div class="inner_wrapper fullwidth">
								        
										<p>I can&#8217;t believe we&#8217;re at the end of 2024, but I suppose that&#8217;s neither here nor there. It <em>is </em>the end of 2024, and traditionally, what we do when it&#8217;s the end of 2024 is: look back on the year of literary adaptations and think about the ones we liked the most. Over a glass of eggnog, naturally.</p>
<p>We&#8217;re living amidst an IP explosion; it&#8217;s almost impossible to keep track of all the adaptations, but at Lit Hub, we tried our damnedst. What follows is a list of our favorites from among the overwhelming profusion of adaptations we&#8217;ve encountered this past year.</p>
<p>We&#8217;ve broken down this list into two categories, &#8220;Film&#8221; and &#8220;TV,&#8221; to keep things extra clear, and marked where you can stream them for free (if they&#8217;re streaming for free).</p>
<p style="text-align: center;">*</p>
<h2 style="text-align: center;"><strong>FILM</strong></h2>
<p><img fetchpriority="high" decoding="async" class="wp-image-147862 aligncenter" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2024/12/1aa7dbd0-8aca-11ef-81f8-1f28bcc5be15-300x169.jpg" sizes="(max-width: 577px) 100vw, 577px" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2024/12/1aa7dbd0-8aca-11ef-81f8-1f28bcc5be15-300x169.jpg 300w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2024/12/1aa7dbd0-8aca-11ef-81f8-1f28bcc5be15-768x432.jpg 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2024/12/1aa7dbd0-8aca-11ef-81f8-1f28bcc5be15-50x28.jpg 50w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2024/12/1aa7dbd0-8aca-11ef-81f8-1f28bcc5be15.jpg 976w" alt="" width="557" height="314" /></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><em><strong>Nickel Boys<br />
</strong></em>Based on: <a href="https://bookshop.org/a/238/9780345804341" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><em>The Nickel Boys</em></a> by Colson Whitehead</p>
<p><span class="LrzXr kno-fv wHYlTd z8gr9e">RaMell Ross’s deft, impressive adaptation of Colson Whitehead’s Pulitzer Prize-winning novel about a sinister, segregated detention camp for boys in the 1950s, is a bracing and commanding achievement—in its handling of narrative but also through its particularly innovative camera use. It is heavy with subjective shots, in ways that tease intimacy but really hold the audience at a distance until the film’s charged, unforgettable climax and denouement. I can’t remember being so riveted in sickly agony and sheer amazement by a film in such a long time. Truly, I’ve never seen a film like this before. You must see it. You must.</span></p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p><img decoding="async" data-attachment-id="247520" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/the-10-best-literary-adaptations-of-2024/30robotdreams-review1-zjtw-superjumbo/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/30robotdreams-review1-zjtw-superJumbo.jpeg" data-orig-size="1998,1080" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;1&quot;}" data-image-title="30robotdreams-review1-zjtw-superJumbo" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="&lt;p&gt;Arcadia Motion Pictures, Lokiz Films, Noodles Production, Les Films du Worso&lt;/p&gt;
" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/30robotdreams-review1-zjtw-superJumbo-300x162.jpeg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/30robotdreams-review1-zjtw-superJumbo-1240x670.jpeg" class="wp-image-247520 aligncenter" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/30robotdreams-review1-zjtw-superJumbo-300x162.jpeg" alt="" width="521" height="281" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/30robotdreams-review1-zjtw-superJumbo-300x162.jpeg 300w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/30robotdreams-review1-zjtw-superJumbo-1240x670.jpeg 1240w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/30robotdreams-review1-zjtw-superJumbo-768x415.jpeg 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/30robotdreams-review1-zjtw-superJumbo-60x32.jpeg 60w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/30robotdreams-review1-zjtw-superJumbo-1536x830.jpeg 1536w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/30robotdreams-review1-zjtw-superJumbo-50x27.jpeg 50w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/30robotdreams-review1-zjtw-superJumbo.jpeg 1998w" sizes="(max-width: 521px) 100vw, 521px" /></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><strong><em>Robot Dreams</em><br />
</strong><em>Based on: </em><a class="product-buy-link external" href="https://www.amazon.com/dp/1250073502?tag=vulture-20&amp;ascsubtag=__vu1219awd__clqzc9cqw00000qb8laprz35y__234002________4________google.com" target="_blank" rel="noopener sponsored,nofollow" data-track-type="product-link" data-track-variant="product - name" data-track-id="UbF5ip" data-merchant-id="234002" data-track-name="&lt;em&gt;Robot Dreams,&lt;/em&gt; by Sara Varon" data-track-option="name" data-track-merchant="Amazon" data-track-manufacturer="Square Fish" data-track-price="8" data-track-currency="$" data-track-badges="" data-track-source="" data-track-medium="" data-track-campaign="" data-track-sponsored="" data-affiliate-subtag="__vu1219awd__clqzc9cqw00000qb8laprz35y__234002________4________google.com" data-affiliate-links-ignore="true" data-aps-asin="1250073502" data-aps-asc-tag="vulture-20" data-aps-asc-subtag="__vu1219awd__clqzc9cqw00000qb8laprz35y__234002________4________google.com"><em>Robot Dreams,</em> by Sara Varon</a></p>
<p>Pablo Berger&#8217;s <em>Robot Dreams </em>is one of the most devastating and beautiful films I&#8217;ve seen in a long while, a riveting dialogue-less adaptation of Sara Varon&#8217;s graphic novel, made in the same artistic style. Nominated for an Oscar for animated film and suitable for all ages, it is the story of Dog, who leads a lonely life in Manhattan, and so orders a robot companion. The two become devoted friends, but when Dog takes Robot to the beach, they find themselves separated and learn that they won&#8217;t be able to reunite for a year or so, each tormented by the length of time, the distance, and the unknowable forces between them.</p>
<p><img decoding="async" class="wp-image-147871 aligncenter" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2024/12/c72f95a473c2c58e54cf4e1d4a9f5ed1-300x200.jpg" sizes="auto, (max-width: 516px) 100vw, 516px" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2024/12/c72f95a473c2c58e54cf4e1d4a9f5ed1-300x200.jpg 300w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2024/12/c72f95a473c2c58e54cf4e1d4a9f5ed1-768x512.jpg 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2024/12/c72f95a473c2c58e54cf4e1d4a9f5ed1-50x33.jpg 50w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2024/12/c72f95a473c2c58e54cf4e1d4a9f5ed1.jpg 960w" alt="" width="516" height="344" /></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><em><strong>Conclave<br />
</strong></em>Based on: <a href="https://bookshop.org/a/238/9780593689585" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><em>Conclave </em></a>by Robert Harris</p>
<p>In <em>Conclave</em>, Ralph Fiennes plays Dean-Cardinal Thomas Lawrence, the Vatican official charged with organizing a papal conclave to elect a new pope, following the death of the previous one. But, once all the cardinals have been sequestered and political schmoozing begins in earnest, Cardinal Lawrence finds himself not only in charge of the proceedings, but also finding out what really happened to the previous pope, whose death seems to have been a bit suspicious.</p>
<p>So, yes, <em>Conclave </em>is a detective story. But Cardinal Lawrence ain’t no Father Brown. This is a tense, staid film… and more than make Lawrence a sleuth, wisely, in all ways, the film makes the WHOLE THING a <em>mystery.</em> I’ll explain. This is a film about a man who, in his vocation to and service of the Church, has lived for a long time accepting the senses of mystery in his life, but who suddenly finds that everything around him is very, very mysterious: the political motivations of his colleagues, the secret ambitions of his friends, and even the Church’s ability to carry out the work of God. In a world of whispers and gossip and secrets and rumors and pleas and deals, Cardinal Lawrence becomes the only man asking questions.</p>
<p><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="247535" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/the-10-best-literary-adaptations-of-2024/the-wild-robot/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/the-wild-robot.jpg" data-orig-size="862,575" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="the-wild-robot" data-image-description="&lt;p&gt;Universal Pictures &lt;/p&gt;
" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/the-wild-robot-300x200.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/the-wild-robot.jpg" class="wp-image-247535 aligncenter" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/the-wild-robot-300x200.jpg" alt="" width="482" height="321" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/the-wild-robot-300x200.jpg 300w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/the-wild-robot-768x512.jpg 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/the-wild-robot-60x40.jpg 60w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/the-wild-robot-50x33.jpg 50w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/the-wild-robot.jpg 862w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 482px) 100vw, 482px" /></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><em><b>The Wild Robot<br />
</b></em><b></b>Based on: <em> <a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780316382007" class="external" target="_blank">The Wild Robot</a></em> by Peter Brown</p>
<p>This lovely, lovely film about a robot named Roz stranded on a desert island is, true to its source material, a beautiful reflection on the relationship between technology and nature.</p>
<p><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="247513" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/the-10-best-literary-adaptations-of-2024/12youngwerther-review-plgv-superjumbo/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/12youngwerther-review-plgv-superJumbo.jpeg" data-orig-size="2048,1366" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;1&quot;}" data-image-title="12youngwerther-review-plgv-superJumbo" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/12youngwerther-review-plgv-superJumbo-300x200.jpeg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/12youngwerther-review-plgv-superJumbo-1240x827.jpeg" class="wp-image-247513 aligncenter" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/12youngwerther-review-plgv-superJumbo-300x200.jpeg" alt="" width="506" height="337" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/12youngwerther-review-plgv-superJumbo-300x200.jpeg 300w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/12youngwerther-review-plgv-superJumbo-1240x827.jpeg 1240w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/12youngwerther-review-plgv-superJumbo-768x512.jpeg 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/12youngwerther-review-plgv-superJumbo-60x40.jpeg 60w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/12youngwerther-review-plgv-superJumbo-1536x1025.jpeg 1536w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/12youngwerther-review-plgv-superJumbo-50x33.jpeg 50w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/12youngwerther-review-plgv-superJumbo.jpeg 2048w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 506px) 100vw, 506px" /></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><strong><em>Young Werther<br />
</em></strong>Based on: <a href="https://bookshop.org/a/238/9780199583027" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><em>The Sorrows of Young Werther,</em></a> by Johann Wolfgang von Goethe</p>
<p>Yes, that&#8217;s right&#8230; there is <a href="https://lithub.com/the-rom-com-of-young-werther-goethes-famous-sadsack-is-getting-a-new-adaptation/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">a new adaptation of Goethe&#8217;s </a><em>The Sorrows of Young Werther. </em>And not only that&#8230; it&#8217;s a romantic comedy. And not only that, it&#8217;s set in the modern day. And not only that&#8230; it&#8217;s good?</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="247516" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/the-10-best-literary-adaptations-of-2024/taste1-tqlc-superjumbo/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/taste1-tqlc-superJumbo.jpeg" data-orig-size="2048,1152" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;1&quot;}" data-image-title="taste1-tqlc-superJumbo" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="&lt;p&gt;Carole Bethuel/IFC Films&lt;/p&gt;
" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/taste1-tqlc-superJumbo-300x169.jpeg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/taste1-tqlc-superJumbo-1240x698.jpeg" class="wp-image-247516 aligncenter" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/taste1-tqlc-superJumbo-300x169.jpeg" alt="" width="497" height="280" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/taste1-tqlc-superJumbo-300x169.jpeg 300w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/taste1-tqlc-superJumbo-1240x698.jpeg 1240w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/taste1-tqlc-superJumbo-768x432.jpeg 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/taste1-tqlc-superJumbo-60x34.jpeg 60w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/taste1-tqlc-superJumbo-1536x864.jpeg 1536w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/taste1-tqlc-superJumbo-50x28.jpeg 50w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/taste1-tqlc-superJumbo.jpeg 2048w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 497px) 100vw, 497px" /></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><strong><em>The Taste of Things<br />
</em></strong>Based on: <em><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/238/9780375760808" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">The Passionate Epicure: La Vie et la Passion de Dodin-Bouffant, Gourmet</a>, </em>by <span class="comma-after-except-last">Marcel Rouff  </span></p>
<p><em>The Taste of Things </em>is a beautiful movie. It’s not a very vegetarian movie, if that’s a useful thing for you to know, but hey, neither is French cuisine, and that is what this movie is about. Well, it’s about more than simply cuisine, even more than <em>cooking</em>… the film, directed by <span class="LrzXr kno-fv wHYlTd z8gr9e">Tran Anh Hung</span>, takes a thorough, holistic, craft-based approach to the epicurean project, from growing ingredients to harvesting them to preparing them to combining them in dishes and combining dishes in courses and combining courses in menus.</p>
<p>Benoît Magimel plays Dodin Bouffant, a wealthy gourmand in rural 19th-century France. Juliette Binoche plays Eugénie, the gifted cook who works at his manor. The two are constant collaborators in every respect: cooking, work, love. Dodin wants to marry Eugénie, but she wants to keep their relationship the way it is, with their shared art at the center. A beautiful and sensual and tender movie.</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="247534" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/the-10-best-literary-adaptations-of-2024/nosferatu_618fa9/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/Nosferatu_618fa9.jpeg" data-orig-size="1200,800" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;1&quot;}" data-image-title="Nosferatu_618fa9" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="&lt;p&gt;FOCUS FEATURES&lt;/p&gt;
" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/Nosferatu_618fa9-300x200.jpeg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/Nosferatu_618fa9.jpeg" class="wp-image-247534 aligncenter" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/Nosferatu_618fa9-300x200.jpeg" alt="" width="503" height="335" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/Nosferatu_618fa9-300x200.jpeg 300w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/Nosferatu_618fa9-768x512.jpeg 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/Nosferatu_618fa9-60x40.jpeg 60w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/Nosferatu_618fa9-50x33.jpeg 50w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/Nosferatu_618fa9.jpeg 1200w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 503px) 100vw, 503px" /></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><em><b>Nosferatu<br />
</b></em>Based on: <a href="https://bookshop.org/a/238/9780141439846" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><em>Dracula </em></a>by Bram Stoker</p>
<p>Good things come to those who wait, and I have been waiting for Robert Eggers&#8217;s <em>Nosferatu </em>adaptation for years. I am very pleased to report that this is a dark, mysterious, and rich adaptation that braids together many different aspects of its cinematic <em>and </em>literary precursors. It comes out on Christmas Day, so lug your crucifixes out of your house and take them to the theater with you!</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<h2 style="text-align: center;"><strong>TV</strong></h2>
<p><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="247532" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/the-10-best-literary-adaptations-of-2024/01_gallery_yoshii-toranaga_armor_0350-h-2024/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/01_GALLERY_YOSHII-TORANAGA_ARMOR_0350-H-2024.jpeg" data-orig-size="1296,730" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;1&quot;}" data-image-title="01_GALLERY_YOSHII-TORANAGA_ARMOR_0350-H-2024" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="&lt;p&gt;Kurt Iswarienko/FX&lt;/p&gt;
" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/01_GALLERY_YOSHII-TORANAGA_ARMOR_0350-H-2024-300x169.jpeg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/01_GALLERY_YOSHII-TORANAGA_ARMOR_0350-H-2024-1240x698.jpeg" class="wp-image-247532 aligncenter" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/01_GALLERY_YOSHII-TORANAGA_ARMOR_0350-H-2024-300x169.jpeg" alt="" width="486" height="274" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/01_GALLERY_YOSHII-TORANAGA_ARMOR_0350-H-2024-300x169.jpeg 300w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/01_GALLERY_YOSHII-TORANAGA_ARMOR_0350-H-2024-1240x698.jpeg 1240w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/01_GALLERY_YOSHII-TORANAGA_ARMOR_0350-H-2024-768x433.jpeg 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/01_GALLERY_YOSHII-TORANAGA_ARMOR_0350-H-2024-60x34.jpeg 60w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/01_GALLERY_YOSHII-TORANAGA_ARMOR_0350-H-2024-50x28.jpeg 50w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/01_GALLERY_YOSHII-TORANAGA_ARMOR_0350-H-2024.jpeg 1296w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 486px) 100vw, 486px" /></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><em><strong>Shogun </strong></em>(Hulu/FX)<br />
Based on: <a href="https://bookshop.org/a/238/9798212173476" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><em>Shogun </em></a>by James Clavell</p>
<p><em>Shogun</em>!! A veritable masterpiece!! If you weren&#8217;t watching <em>Shogun </em>when it aired, I&#8217;m not sure what your excuse could have been, but it&#8217;s all right: you can watch it now! Based on James Clavell&#8217;s 1975 novel about 17th-century Japan, it&#8217;s the story of Dutch arrival on Japanese shores, and the cataclysmic consequences for all involved. Plus, it features an unreal performance from Hiroyuki Sanada.</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="247533" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/the-10-best-literary-adaptations-of-2024/bad_monkey_photo_010801-e1721777546555/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/Bad_Monkey_Photo_010801-e1721777546555.jpeg" data-orig-size="1440,810" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;1&quot;}" data-image-title="Bad_Monkey_Photo_010801-e1721777546555" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="&lt;p&gt;Apple TV+&lt;/p&gt;
" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/Bad_Monkey_Photo_010801-e1721777546555-300x169.jpeg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/Bad_Monkey_Photo_010801-e1721777546555-1240x698.jpeg" class="wp-image-247533 aligncenter" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/Bad_Monkey_Photo_010801-e1721777546555-300x169.jpeg" alt="" width="490" height="276" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/Bad_Monkey_Photo_010801-e1721777546555-300x169.jpeg 300w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/Bad_Monkey_Photo_010801-e1721777546555-1240x698.jpeg 1240w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/Bad_Monkey_Photo_010801-e1721777546555-768x432.jpeg 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/Bad_Monkey_Photo_010801-e1721777546555-60x34.jpeg 60w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/Bad_Monkey_Photo_010801-e1721777546555-50x28.jpeg 50w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/Bad_Monkey_Photo_010801-e1721777546555.jpeg 1440w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 490px) 100vw, 490px" /></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><em><strong>Bad Monkey</strong></em> (Apple TV+)<br />
Based on: Carl Hiaasen’s <a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780446556156" class="external" target="_blank"><i>Bad Monkey</i></a> (2013)</p>
<p>I was pleasantly surprised by <em>Bad Monkey</em>, the groovy new adaptation of Carol Hiaasen&#8217;s classic Florida PI story. Vince Vaughn is Andrey Yancy, a down-and-out former detective living in Key West, who becomes embroiled in a mystery after a severed arm is found on a fishing trip. It&#8217;s bright and bubbly enough as much as you&#8217;d want for a neo-noir, and more than plenty sultry and cheeky. A good alternative for those not headed to the Keys for the winter holidays.</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="247408" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/the-10-best-literary-adaptations-of-2024/03ripley-mczb-superjumbo/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/03ripley-mczb-superJumbo.jpeg" data-orig-size="2048,1365" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;1&quot;}" data-image-title="03ripley-mczb-superJumbo" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/03ripley-mczb-superJumbo-300x200.jpeg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/03ripley-mczb-superJumbo-1240x826.jpeg" class="wp-image-247408 aligncenter" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/03ripley-mczb-superJumbo-300x200.jpeg" alt="" width="490" height="326" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/03ripley-mczb-superJumbo-300x200.jpeg 300w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/03ripley-mczb-superJumbo-1240x826.jpeg 1240w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/03ripley-mczb-superJumbo-768x512.jpeg 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/03ripley-mczb-superJumbo-60x40.jpeg 60w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/03ripley-mczb-superJumbo-1536x1024.jpeg 1536w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/03ripley-mczb-superJumbo-50x33.jpeg 50w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/03ripley-mczb-superJumbo.jpeg 2048w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 490px) 100vw, 490px" /></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><em><strong>Ripley</strong></em> (Netflix)<br />
Based on: <a href="https://bookshop.org/a/238/9780393332148" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><em>The Talented Mr. Ripley</em></a> by Patricia Highsmith</p>
<p>We didn&#8217;t really need another adaptation of <em>The Talented Mr. Ripley, </em>but I&#8217;m very glad we got one. Developed, written, and directed by Steven Zaillian, <em>Ripley </em>unfolds as a noir, in punchy, digital black-and-white. The thing about this new series, is that its leading actor, Andrew Scott, is incredibly good. He’s incredibly good in it, and he’s incredibly good in everything. I might even say that he’s the best actor working today.</p>
<p>In the first shot of Scott’s face, his dark eyes look black and cold, like pools of crude oil. In <em>Ripley,</em> Scott has managed to evacuate almost all humanity and feeling from his body; he embodies the sharp contrast of a body which appears to be human but lacks a human’s soul. This mode of characterization makes for a compelling antihero, but also feels rather like an intervention in the <em>Ripley </em>canon.</p>
<p>Anthony Minghella’s <em>The Talented Mr. Ripley </em>is nothing if not emotional; it stars Matt Damon as a young, giddy and thoroughly disturbed interloper who falls in love with a beautiful man and a beautiful lifestyle, and then does whatever he can to preserve whatever he can have of it. It is as heartbreaking as it’s terrifying, a study in explosive pathos and even, maybe, how the pursuit of community only results in greater loneliness. But the novel, written in 1955 by Patricia Highsmith, offers us a slicker, slimier sociopath. We’ve seen an unfeeling Ripley before, but not in a while, and not as well as the one Andrew Scott offers to us, which is an awkward but conniving lizard-man.</p>
										
																				
																		
										<div class="post_wrapper author">
											<div id="about_the_author">
												<div class="gravatar"><a href="https://lithub.com/author/oliviarutigliano/"><img src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2021/12/Olivia-Rutigliano-100x100.jpg" width="100" height="100" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2021/12/Olivia-Rutigliano-300x300.jpg 2x" alt="Olivia Rutigliano" class="avatar avatar-100 wp-user-avatar wp-user-avatar-100 alignnone photo" /></a></div>
												<div class="description author withsidebar">
													<h6><a href="https://lithub.com/author/oliviarutigliano/">Olivia Rutigliano</a></h6>
													Olivia Rutigliano is an Editor at Lit Hub and CrimeReads, and a book editor at their parent company Grove Atlantic. Her other work appears in Vanity Fair, Vulture, Lapham's Quarterly, the Los Angeles Review of Books, Public Books, The Baffler, Bright Wall/Dark Room, Politics/Letters, The Toast, Truly Adventurous, PBS Television, and elsewhere. She has a PhD from the departments of English/comparative literature and theatre at Columbia University, where she was the Marion E. Ponsford fellow. She is on instagram at @oldebean and twitter at @oldrutigliano.																									</div>
											</div><br class="clear"/><br/>
										</div>

